webpackJsonp([0xe4655ca25139e800],{"./node_modules/json-loader/index.js!./.cache/json/mathematics-chain-rule-introduction.json":function(n,e){n.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{html:"<h1>Chain Rule Introduction</h1>\n<p>Chain Rule is used to compute the derivative of a composition of functions.</p>\n<p>Let <em>F</em> be a real valued function which is a composite of two functions <em>f</em> and <em>g</em>  i.e. <code>F(x) = f(g(x))</code>and both f(x) and g(x) are differentiable.\nLet the derivative D{F(x)} is denoted as F’(x).</p>\n<p>By Chain Rule, </p>\n<h4><em><code>F'(x) = f'(g(x)).g'(x)</code></em></h4>\n<p>Suppose, g(x) = t then F(x) = f(g(x)) can be rewritten as F(x)=f(t)\nthen in Leibniz’s notation Chain Rule can be rewritten as : </p>\n<h4><code>d(F)/dx = df/dt . dt/dx</code></h4>\n<h3>Example 1.   To compute derivative of sin(ax+b)</h3>\n<p>Solution : The function can be visualized as a composite of two functions. F(x)= f(g(x))</p>\n<p>t= g(x)= ax+b  and f(t)=sin(t)</p>\n<p>f(t)=sin(t) => df/dt = cos(t)</p>\n<p>t= g(x) = ax+b => dt/dx = a</p>\n<p>Now by Chain Rule: </p>\n<p>d(F)/dx = df/dt . dt/dx</p>\n<p>=> d(F)/dx = a . cost(t) = a.cos(ax+b)</p>\n<p>OR </p>\n<p>We can directly apply the formula F’(x) = f’(g(x)).g’(x) = cos(ax+b) . a</p>\n<h2>For a function composite of more than two function :</h2>\n<p>Let <em>F</em> be a real valued function which is a composite of four functions <em>r s t u</em>  i.e. <code>F(x)=r(s(t(u(x))))</code> and all the functions <em>r(x) s(x) t(x) u(x)</em> are differentiable.\nLet the derivative D{F(x)} is denoted as F’(x).</p>\n<p>By Chain Rule, </p>\n<h4><em><code>F'(x) = r'(s(t(u(x)))).s'(t(u(x))).t'(u(x)).u'(x)</code></em></h4>\n<p>Suppose, a = u(x), b = t(a), c = s(b) then F(x)=r(s(t(u(x)))) can be re-written as F(x)=r(c) </p>\n<p>then, F(x)=r(c) => d(F)/dx = dr/dc . dc/dx                ___ (eqn 1)</p>\n<p>c = s(b) => dc/dx = ds/db . db/dx                          ___ (eqn 2)</p>\n<p>b = t(a) => db/dx = dt/da . da/dx                          ___ (eqn 3)</p>\n<p>a = u(x) => da/dx = du/dx                                  ___ (eqn 4)</p>\n<p>Putting the value of eqn 2 3 4 in eqn 1, we will get :</p>\n<h4><code>d(F)/dx = dr/dc . ds/db . dt/da . du/dx</code></h4>\n<h3>Example 2.   To compute derivative of sin(cos((mx+n)^3))</h3>\n<p>Solution : The function can be visualized as a composite of four functions. F(x)= r(s(t(u(x))))</p>\n<p>where a = u(x) = mx+n</p>\n<p>b = t(a) = a^3 </p>\n<p>c = s(b) = cos(b) then F(x)=r(s(t(u(x)))) can be re-written as F(x)= r(c) =sin(c) </p>\n<p>Now, By chain rule :\nd(F)/dx = dr/dc . ds/db . dt/da . du/dx</p>\n<p>=> d(F)/dx = cos(c) . -sin(b) . 3a^2 . m</p>\n<p>=> d(F)/dx = cos(cos((mx+n)^3)) . -sin((mx+n)^3)) . 3(mx+n)^2 . m</p>\n<p>OR </p>\n<p>We can directly apply the formula, </p>\n<p>F’(x) = r’(s(t(u(x)))).s’(t(u(x))).t’(u(x)).u’(x) = cos(cos((mx+n)^3)) . -sin((mx+n)^3)) . 3(mx+n)^2 . m</p>",fields:{slug:"/mathematics/chain-rule-introduction/"},frontmatter:{title:"Chain Rule Introduction"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/mathematics/chain-rule-introduction/"}}}});
